<H1>Problem A</H1>
<H2>The Poor Giant</H2>
<H4><B>Input:</B> Standard Input</H4>
<H4><B>Output:</B> Standard Output</H4>
<H4><B>Time Limit:</B> 1 second</H4>
<P>On a table, there are n apples, the i-th apple has the weight=20
k+i(1&lt;=3Di&lt;=3Dn). Exactly one of the apples is sweet, lighter =
apples are all=20
bitter, while heavier apples are all sour. The giant wants to know which =
one is=20
sweet, the only thing he can do is to eat apples. He hates bitter apples =
and=20
sour apples, what should he do?<BR>For examples, n=3D4, k=3D0, the =
apples are of=20
weight 1, 2, 3, 4. The gaint can first eat apple #2.<BR>if #2 is sweet, =
the=20
answer is #2<BR>if #2 is sour, the answer is #1<BR>if #2 is bitter, the =
answer=20
might be #3 or #4, then he eats #3, he'll know the answer regardless of =
the=20
taste of #3<BR>The poor gaint should be prepared to eat some bad apples =
in order=20
to know which one is sweet. Let's compute the total weight of apples he =
must eat=20
in all cases.<BR>#1 is sweet: 2<BR>#2 is sweet: 2<BR>#3 is sweet: 2 + 3 =
=3D 5<BR>
#4 is sweet: 2 + 3 =3D 5<BR>The total weights =3D 2 + 2 + 5 + 5 =3D =
14.<BR>This is not=20
optimal. If he eats apple #1, then he eats total weight of 1, 3, 3, 3 =
when apple=20
#1, #2, #3 and #4 are sweet respectively. This yields a solution of =
1+3+3+3=3D13,=20
beating 14. What is the minimal total weight of apples in all cases? =
</P>
<P>
